Azure offers a broad portfolio of managed database services. This topic covers the two most widely used: Azure S-Q-L — the family of managed relational database services built on S-Q-L Server — and Azure Cosmos D-B, a globally distributed multi-model NoSQL database with single-digit millisecond latency. Azure S-Q-L maps broadly to Amazon R-D-S for S-Q-L Server, and Cosmos D-B maps to a combination of DynamoDB and DocumentDB on A-W-S.

Let us start with the Azure S-Q-L family.

Azure S-Q-L comes in three deployment options with increasing levels of control. Azure S-Q-L Database is a fully managed P-a-a-S service — Azure handles O-S patching, backups, high availability, and scaling, and you manage only the database. Azure S-Q-L Managed Instance provides near 100% compatibility with on-premises S-Q-L Server and is deployed inside your V-Net. S-Q-L Server on an Azure V-M is I-a-a-S — you manage the O-S and S-Q-L Server installation and have full control.

Azure S-Q-L Database supports three deployment models. A single database has its own guaranteed compute resources. An elastic pool lets multiple databases share a pool of compute, which is cost-effective when you have many databases with variable and unpredictable load — databases that are busy at different times share the pool. The serverless compute tier automatically pauses the database after a configurable idle period — billing stops during the pause — and auto-resumes on the next connection, which takes about one minute. Serverless is ideal for development databases and workloads with intermittent usage.

Azure S-Q-L Database uses two purchasing models. The v-Core model is recommended — you choose the number of virtual cores and a service tier. The General Purpose tier uses remote S-S-D storage and is suitable for most workloads. The Business Critical tier uses local S-S-D storage and is built on a three-node Always On Availability Group — it includes a readable secondary replica at no extra cost, has faster failover of around 5 to 10 seconds compared to 20 to 30 seconds for General Purpose, and is suited for high I-O, low-latency workloads. The Hyperscale tier supports databases up to 100 terabytes using a distributed storage layer and allows you to add read replicas that scale out instantly — use it for very large databases. The older D-T-U model bundles compute, I-O, and storage into a single unit — it is legacy and the v-Core model is preferred for new workloads.

Azure S-Q-L Database takes automated backups: a full backup weekly, a differential backup every 12 to 24 hours, and log backups every 5 to 10 minutes. This enables point-in-time restore to any point within the retention window, which you configure between 1 and 35 days. For compliance scenarios requiring longer retention, Long-Term Retention extends backup storage up to 10 years using Azure Blob Storage.

Azure S-Q-L Managed Instance is the right choice for lift-and-shift migrations from on-premises S-Q-L Server when the application depends on instance-level features that S-Q-L Database does not support — such as S-Q-L Agent for scheduled jobs, cross-database queries, C-L-R extensions, Service Broker, linked servers, and instance-level collation settings. S-Q-L Managed Instance is deployed using V-Net injection into a dedicated subnet, so it has a private I-P and is not exposed to the public internet.

Now let us look at Azure S-Q-L security.

For authentication, Entra I-D authentication is recommended — users and service principals authenticate using an Entra I-D token, which supports Managed Identity for applications. S-Q-L authentication with username and password is available but should be avoided in production. You set an Entra I-D administrator on the logical S-Q-L server, and that account can then grant database access to other Entra I-D users and groups.

For network access, the simplest option is public endpoint with firewall rules allowing specific I-P ranges or Azure services. Service endpoints route V-Net traffic over the Azure backbone. Private endpoints give the S-Q-L server a private I-P in your V-Net — this is the recommended approach for production, resolving through the privatelink dot database dot windows dot net D-N-S zone.

All data at rest is protected by Transparent Data Encryption, or T-D-E, using A-E-S 256-bit encryption — it is always on by default. You can use service-managed keys where Azure handles everything, or customer-managed keys stored in Azure Key Vault where you control the key rotation and can revoke access.

Microsoft Defender for S-Q-L adds vulnerability assessment scans and Advanced Threat Protection that detects anomalous access patterns and potential S-Q-L injection attacks. Dynamic Data Masking lets you mask sensitive column values — such as credit card numbers or email addresses — for non-privileged users without changing the underlying stored data. Always Encrypted goes further, encrypting specific columns so that Azure never sees the plaintext — only the client application that holds the encryption key can read those values. Row-Level Security filters the rows returned to a user based on their identity, enforced transparently at the database engine level.

Now let us look at Azure Cosmos D-B.

Azure Cosmos D-B is a fully managed, globally distributed, multi-model NoSQL database. It guarantees single-digit millisecond latency at the 99th percentile for both reads and writes, a 99.999% availability S-L-A with multi-region writes, and automatic indexing of all fields with no schema definition required.

The resource hierarchy has four levels. A Cosmos D-B account is the top-level resource. Inside it you create databases, which are logical namespaces. Inside a database you create containers — the container is the unit of scale, where throughput and storage are provisioned. Inside a container you store items, which are called documents in the NoSQL A-P-I, rows in the Cassandra A-P-I, nodes and edges in the Gremlin A-P-I, and so on.

Cosmos D-B is multi-model — you choose the A-P-I when creating the account. The NoSQL A-P-I, also called the Core S-Q-L A-P-I, stores J-S-O-N documents and supports S-Q-L-like query syntax. It has the richest Cosmos D-B feature set and is the recommended default. The MongoDB A-P-I uses the MongoDB wire protocol — existing MongoDB applications can connect without code changes. The Cassandra A-P-I uses C-Q-L and supports Cassandra workload migration. The Gremlin A-P-I is for graph data — vertices and edges — used in social graphs and recommendation engines. The Table A-P-I provides a key-value model compatible with Azure Table Storage. And the PostgreSQL v-Core A-P-I provides distributed PostgreSQL using Citus for sharded relational workloads.

The partition key is the single most important design decision in Cosmos D-B. It determines how data is physically distributed across logical partitions. Choose a key with high cardinality — many distinct values — and one that distributes reads and writes evenly. A hot partition occurs when too many operations target the same partition key value and can exhaust the partition's throughput. Queries that include the partition key are efficient, staying within a single partition. Cross-partition queries fan out to all partitions and consume more R-Us. Each logical partition can hold up to 20 gigabytes. If no natural single field provides good distribution, you can create a synthetic partition key by combining two fields — for example tenant I-D plus date.

Now let us cover throughput and capacity.

Cosmos D-B measures all operations in Request Units per second, or R-U slash s. One R-U is defined as the cost of reading a 1 kilobyte document by its I-D. A write of 1 kilobyte costs approximately 5 R-Us. A simple single-partition query costs around 2.5 R-Us. Cross-partition queries cost more proportionally to the number of partitions scanned.

There are three throughput provisioning modes. Manual provisioned R-U slash s gives a fixed throughput — you pay for the provisioned amount regardless of usage, suitable for predictable steady workloads. Autoscale automatically scales between 10% and 100% of a configured maximum — for example, with a maximum of 4,000 R-U slash s, Cosmos D-B scales down to 400 R-U slash s during low traffic and back up instantly on demand. You pay for the peak reached in each hour. Serverless mode charges per R-U consumed with no pre-provisioned throughput — ideal for development, testing, and sporadically accessed workloads.

Throughput can be provisioned at the database level — shared across all containers in the database — or at the container level for dedicated throughput. Cosmos D-B also provides a free tier: 1,000 R-U slash s and 25 gigabytes of storage perpetually free, one free tier account per subscription.

Now let us cover global distribution and consistency.

You can add or remove Azure regions from a Cosmos D-B account with a single click, and data is automatically replicated to all configured regions. Cosmos D-B offers five tunable consistency levels that trade off between consistency and performance. Strong consistency means every read returns the latest write — analogous to a traditional relational database, but at the cost of higher latency because the write must be confirmed across all replicas. Bounded Staleness means reads lag behind writes by at most a configurable number of versions or seconds — useful for near-real-time leaderboards. Session consistency is the default — within a single client session, you always read your own writes; other clients may see slightly stale data. This works well for most user-facing applications. Consistent Prefix guarantees you never see out-of-order writes but may see older data — suitable for social feeds and I-o-T telemetry. Eventual consistency provides the lowest latency with no ordering guarantee — use it for scenarios like click counting or likes where absolute accuracy is not required.

By default, one region is the write region and all others are read regions. Enabling multi-region writes allows writes in any configured region, minimising write latency globally. When two regions write the same item simultaneously, a conflict occurs and is resolved either by Last-Writer-Wins using a timestamp property, or by a custom merge procedure written as a JavaScript stored procedure.

Let us now look at key Cosmos D-B features.

Cosmos D-B automatically indexes every property in every document by default — you do not need to define a schema or create indexes manually. You can customise the indexing policy per container to exclude paths you never query, saving R-U cost and storage. Composite indexes are required when you want to sort on multiple fields in a query. Spatial indexes support geospatial queries.

The Change Feed is a persistent ordered log of every insert and update to items in a container. Deletes are not captured by default — a soft-delete pattern is recommended where you add a deleted flag before removing items. The Change Feed is commonly used to trigger Azure Functions when data changes, to materialise read-optimised views in a secondary container, for real-time stream processing, and as an audit log.

Time to Live, or T-T-L, lets you automatically expire and delete items after a specified number of seconds. You set T-T-L at the container level as a default, and can override it per item. This is useful for session tokens, temporary data, and records with retention policies — no manual cleanup job required.

Azure Synapse Link enables the analytical store — a fully isolated, automatically synchronised columnar copy of your Cosmos D-B data. You can query it directly from Azure Synapse Analytics using Spark pools or Serverless S-Q-L without any E-T-L pipeline and without impacting transactional performance.

To summarise. Use Azure S-Q-L Database for relational workloads — choose General Purpose for most applications, Business Critical for high I-O with fast failover and a readable secondary, Hyperscale for very large databases, and Serverless for intermittent development workloads. Use S-Q-L Managed Instance for lift-and-shift migrations that require S-Q-L Agent, cross-database queries, or C-L-R. Use Cosmos D-B for globally distributed, low-latency, flexible-schema workloads where millisecond response time and multi-region availability are requirements. Design partition keys carefully for even distribution. Use Session consistency as the default and tune up to Strong only when needed for transactions. Leverage the Change Feed for event-driven architectures and Synapse Link for analytics without impacting transactional performance.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Cache for Redis and other Azure database services including PostgreSQL, MySQL, and MariaDB.
